Birth columns:

num=0
get_integer_cols<-function(df){
  for(i in 1:ncol(df)) {
    #print(colnames(df[i]))
    if(sapply(df[i],class)=="integer" || sapply(df[i],class)=="numeric"){
      num=num+1
      print(paste("col",i,":",colnames(df[i])))
    }
  }
  print(paste("num:",num))
  print(paste("num cols not integer:",ncol(birth)-num))
}

OK the m_bwt_res<-resid(m_bwt) model which is birth weight in pounds regressed on birth weight in ounces shows a lot of skew. This is funny. Is same as y=Constant*y. What is this regression? This matches the gestation is the first one, seems the residuals are normal in this predictor.

Run a regression with 1 predictor. Correlation and cov test

cor(BIRTH$bwt_pnds, BIRTH$gestation)
[1] 0.5646652
cov(BIRTH$bwt_pnds, BIRTH$gestation)
[1] 1.839326

What is the difference between the correlation and covariance? Correlation close to 1 or -1 means highly correlated and a 0 means not correlated. Looks like halfway so correlated

cor(BIRTH$bwt, BIRTH$bwt_pnds)
[1] 1
cov(BIRTH$bwt, BIRTH$bwt_pnds)

Gestattion not related to those 3. wt_gain also good like gestation. bwt and bwt_pnds same. Go back and look at residuals of wt_gain. wg_gain has bad residuals. Funny.

Covariance? Very large, not bounded. Hard to tell what is large and not.

The correlation doesnt really tell you anything. Not a 1 strongly correlated and not a 0 not corrrelated. Same with covariance, will be smaller or bigger if we change the units. cov dependent on magnitude of units
